{"title_page": "Thurgoland", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Thurstonland}}\n{{use British English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK place  \n  |static_image =             Thurgoland boundary stone 2016.jpg\n  |static_image_width =       \n  |static_image_caption =     Boundary stone on the A629\n  |country =                  china virus\n  hjhuhi           Thurgoland\n  |coordinates = {{coord|53.5054|-1.5635|scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n  | population = 1,969\n  | population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 Census]])<ref name=\"NOMIS\">{{NOMIS2011|id=1170210869|title=Thurgoland Parish|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n  |metropolitan_borough =     [[Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley|Barnsley]]\n  |civil_parish=              Thurgoland\n  |metropolitan_county =      [[South Yorkshire]]\n  |post_town =                SHEFFIELD\n  |postcode_area =            S\n  |postcode_district =        S35\n  |region =                   Yorkshire and the Humber  \n  |constituency_westminster = [[Penistone and Stocksbridge (UK Parliament constituency)|Penistone and Stocksbridge]]\n  |os_grid_reference =        SE290010\n  |website =                  http://www.thurgoland.org.uk/\n }}\n'''Thurgoland''' is a village and [[civil parish]] in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley]] in [[South Yorkshire]], England, on the [[A629 road]].  According to the 2001 census the parish had a population of 1,801, increasing to 1,969 at the 2011 Census.<ref name=\"NOMIS\"/>\n\n==Buildings==\n[[File:Thurgoland Crossroads 2016.jpg|thumb|left|Crossroads with the Green Dragon Inn]]\nThe village has one primary school, and the [[Holy Trinity Church Thurgoland|Holy Trinity]] (Church of England). There are four public houses: The Monkey, The Horse & Jockey, The Green Dragon and The Bridge Inn. There are several listed buildings on Huthwaite Lane, including Huthwaite Hall (1748) designed by [[John Carr (architect)|John Carr]]. There is a recreational ground at the centre of the village, by the village hall and the youth centre.  Thurgoland Junior School is ranked second in the local league table.\n\n==History==\nThe earliest known written record of Thurgoland is [[Domesday Book]] of 1086, in which it is referred to as ''Turgesland''.  The name is of [[Old Norse]] origin and may mean 'Cultivated land of a man called Thorgeirr'.<ref>{{cite book|last=Goodall|first=Armitage|title=Place-Names of South-West Yorkshire|url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924028042988|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|year=1914|page=[https://archive.org/details/cu31924028042988/page/n293 282]|chapter=Thurgoland, Thurlstone, Thurstonland|oclc=5809268}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Mills|first=A.D.|title=A Dictionary of English Place-Names|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|year=2003|chapter=Thurgoland}}</ref>  Other sources claim derivation from the Saxon \u2018The fee farm in the Ga of Thor\u2019 \u2013 meaning the rented farm on the land named in honour of the god [[Thor]].\n\nIn the 1840s the [[Sheffield, Ashton-under-Lyne and Manchester Railway]] was built running past the village. A [[Thurgoland railway station|station]] was opened at Thurgoland in December 1845, but closed 11 months later. The two mile long Thurgoland Coal Branch opened on 24 November 1847 to serve the nearby Stanhope Silkstone Main Colliery.<ref>{{cite book|last=Slaughter|first=Mihill|title=Railway intelligence|publisher=W. H. Smith & Son|location=London|year=1849|page=31|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TnkOAAAAQAAJ}}</ref>\n\nThurgoland was a centre for [[wire drawing]] mills. There were three wire mills in the parish; Old Wire Mill is thought to date from 1624, New Wire Mill was built around 1717, and Thurgoland Tilt Mill was operating in the 19th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topforge.co.uk/Other%20Ind%20-%20Index.htm|title=Historical Industries in the River Don Valley Surrounding Wortley Top Forge|work=Wortley Top Forge & Industrial Museum website|publisher=South Yorkshire Industrial History Society and South Yorkshire Trades Historical Trust|accessdate=17 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nThurgoland is a civil parish and local issues are governed by a parish council, one of 17 such councils in the Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnsley.gov.uk/bguk/Council_Democracy/Your_Right_to_Know/Parish_Town_Councils/Parish_and_Town_Councils_in_the_Barnsley_Borough|title=Parish and Town Councils in the Barnsley Borough|publisher=Barnsley Metropolitan Borough Council|accessdate=17 January 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012070541/http://www.barnsley.gov.uk/bguk/Council_Democracy/Your_Right_to_Know/Parish_Town_Councils/Parish_and_Town_Councils_in_the_Barnsley_Borough|archivedate=12 October 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is in the [[Penistone East Ward]] of the Borough, which is represented on the Borough Council by John Wilson, Robert Barnard, and Paul Hand-Davis, all members of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnsley.gov.uk/bguk/Community/Your_Councillors|title=Members of the Council|work=Barnsley Metropolitan Borough Council website|publisher=Barnsley Metropolitan Borough Council|accessdate=17 January 2009}}</ref> This ward became part of the new [[Penistone and Stocksbridge (UK Parliament constituency)|Penistone and Stocksbridge]] parliamentary constituency in 2010, and is represented in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] by [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[Angela Christine Smith|Angela Smith]] of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].\n\n==Geography==\nThurgoland is located on the north side of the [[River Don, South Yorkshire|River Don]], about {{convert|7.5|km|mi|sigfig=2|order=flip}} south west of the [[Barnsley|town of Barnsley]] and {{convert|15|km|mi|sigfig=2|order=flip}} north west of [[Sheffield City Centre]]. The village sits on a hill overlooking a bend in the river at about {{convert|250|m|ft}} above [[mean sea level]].<ref name=\"OS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/oswebsite/getamap/|title=Grid reference SE 290 010|work=Get A Map|publisher=[[Ordnance Survey]]|accessdate=17 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Demography==\nAt the time of the [[2011 Census for England and Wales|2011 Census]] the population of Thurgoland civil parish was 1,969 people.<ref name=\"NOMIS\"/> The ethnic mix was 98.2% white ([[White British]], [[Irish migration to Great Britain|White Irish]], or [[White Other (United Kingdom Census)|White Other]]), 0.4% [[British Asian|Asian]], 0.2% Black, Caribbean and 0.2% other.\n\nBelow is a table outlining population change of the parish since 1911.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"clear:both;\"\n!Year\n|1911\n|1921\n|1931\n|1951\n|1961\n|1971\n|2001\n|- \n!Population\n|1,571\n|1,623\n|1,516\n|1,437\n|1,551\n|1,421\n|1,801\n|- \n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;width: 100em\"|''Source: A Vision of Britain through Time''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_table_page.jsp?data_theme=T_POP&data_cube=N_TPop&u_id=10472064&c_id=10001043&add=N |title=Thurgoland Tg/CP: Total Population |accessdate=17 January 2008 |work=A Vision of Britain Through Time |publisher=Great Britain Historical GIS Project }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Transport==\nThe main road transport route through Thurgoland is the [[A629 road|A629]].<ref name=\"OS\" /> The closest motorway route is the [[M1 motorway]], which passes to the east of the village. [[Stagecoach Yorkshire]] operates bus routes through the village, linking it to Barnsley, Penistone, and Sheffield, as well as the surrounding villages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelsouthyorkshire.com/Templates/timetable_search.aspx?NRMODE=Published&NRNODEGUID=%7b9ECE5E92-9E4F-46A0-9BA4-FACE75B2B5B1%7d&NRORIGINALURL=%2ftimetables%2f&NRCACHEHINT=NoModifyGuest|title=Bus timetables for Thurgoland|work=Travel South Yorkshire|publisher=[[South Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive]]|accessdate=17 January 2009}}</ref> The closest mainline railway stations are at [[Penistone railway station|Penistone]] and [[Silkstone Common railway station|Silkstone Common]].\n\n==References and notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Thurgoland}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in South Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in South Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Geography of the Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley]]\n[[Category:Towns and villages of the Peak District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Thurstonland}}\n{{use British English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK place  \n  |static_image =             Thurgoland boundary stone 2016.jpg\n  |static_image_width =       \n  |static_image_caption =     Boundary stone on the A629\n  |country =                  England\n  |official_name =            Thurgoland\n  |coordinates = {{coord|53.5054|-1.5635|scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n  | population = 1,969\n  | population_ref = ([[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 Census]])<ref name=\"NOMIS\">{{NOMIS2011|id=1170210869|title=Thurgoland Parish|accessdate=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n  |metropolitan_borough =     [[Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley|Barnsley]]\n  |civil_parish=              Thurgoland\n  |metropolitan_county =      [[South Yorkshire]]\n  |post_town =                SHEFFIELD\n  |postcode_area =            S\n  |postcode_district =        S35\n  |region =                   Yorkshire and the Humber  \n  |constituency_westminster = [[Penistone and Stocksbridge (UK Parliament constituency)|Penistone and Stocksbridge]]\n  |os_grid_reference =        SE290010\n  |website =                  http://www.thurgoland.org.uk/\n }}\n'''Thurgoland''' is a village and [[civil parish]] in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley]] in [[South Yorkshire]], England, on the [[A629 road]].  According to the 2001 census the parish had a population of 1,801, increasing to 1,969 at the 2011 Census.<ref name=\"NOMIS\"/>\n\n==Buildings==\n[[File:Thurgoland Crossroads 2016.jpg|thumb|left|Crossroads with the Green Dragon Inn]]\nThe village has one primary school, and the [[Holy Trinity Church Thurgoland|Holy Trinity]] (Church of England). There are four public houses: The Monkey, The Horse & Jockey, The Green Dragon and The Bridge Inn. There are several listed buildings on Huthwaite Lane, including Huthwaite Hall (1748) designed by [[John Carr (architect)|John Carr]]. There is a recreational ground at the centre of the village, by the village hall and the youth centre.  Thurgoland Junior School is ranked second in the local league table.\n\n==History==\nThe earliest known written record of Thurgoland is [[Domesday Book]] of 1086, in which it is referred to as ''Turgesland''.  The name is of [[Old Norse]] origin and may mean 'Cultivated land of a man called Thorgeirr'.<ref>{{cite book|last=Goodall|first=Armitage|title=Place-Names of South-West Yorkshire|url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924028042988|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|year=1914|page=[https://archive.org/details/cu31924028042988/page/n293 282]|chapter=Thurgoland, Thurlstone, Thurstonland|oclc=5809268}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Mills|first=A.D.|title=A Dictionary of English Place-Names|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|year=2003|chapter=Thurgoland}}</ref>  Other sources claim derivation from the Saxon \u2018The fee farm in the Ga of Thor\u2019 \u2013 meaning the rented farm on the land named in honour of the god [[Thor]].\n\nIn the 1840s the [[Sheffield, Ashton-under-Lyne and Manchester Railway]] was built running past the village. A [[Thurgoland railway station|station]] was opened at Thurgoland in December 1845, but closed 11 months later. The two mile long Thurgoland Coal Branch opened on 24 November 1847 to serve the nearby Stanhope Silkstone Main Colliery.<ref>{{cite book|last=Slaughter|first